update_self_containment (scene-scale): The input is a FULL SCENE (or quest
update). Can it stand on its own as a unit of reading?

0.0 = unreadable without memory of prior scenes — opens mid-thought, ends
      mid-thought, references unexplained proper nouns.
0.3 = partially legible; some orientation is present but major threads are
      dangling on entry.
0.5 = readable but lossy — reader will miss emotional stakes without prior
      context.
0.7 = opens with enough orientation (who/where/what-is-at-stake) and closes
      with a clear scene-beat; new reader can follow the action.
1.0 = crisp, self-contained scene. Opening paragraphs plant necessary
      context by action, not exposition; closing beat lands without
      requiring prior-scene callbacks.

Anchors:
  HIGH: a quest update that opens with the protagonist arriving at a known
        place, re-names relevant NPCs in dialogue, and ends on a concrete
        beat.
  MID : a chapter that assumes you remember a name mentioned once, three
        chapters ago.
  LOW : a scene that opens with "She did it anyway" and closes with
        "And that was when everything changed" referring to unstated events.
